<b>stacking ideas - </b>8/28/01 12:19:37 PM<br>~ <b>Jernigans Jubalson</b><blockquote><br>    This song is an incredable song in a group.  The area it effects is small enough to help debuff all the mobs that your group is fighting and small enough to keep you from attracting new ones.  Stack this song with Hymm of Restoration and Anthem de Arms.  With these three songs you'll be healing your group, lowering the mobs' ac and attack speed, and increasing your groups str and attack speed!  You'll be twisting this till you get Psalm of Warmth (or Selo's Constant Chain when fighting only one mob).</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>One of our best &quot;group-friendly&quot; songs - </b>5/11/01 4:45:20 PM<br>~ <b>Kaearia</b><blockquote>Only two classes in the game get an area effect (AE) slow - bards at level 20 (this song), and shaman at level 58.  So for a large segment of the game, AE slowing is an ability &quot;unique&quot; to bards. <br><br>It's a great song, one of our best when grouped with an enchanter.  Most high level bards won't tell you to use it because they rarely used it themselves - they grew up when slow stacking was bugged and this song would overwrite the (much better) slow cast by a shaman or enchanter.  This has since been fixed.  Fire up this song on a multi-mob pull and it'll slow the entire pull, aggro stuff onto you instead of the enchanter or cleric, reduce the chance of your casters being interrupted, and provide a quick-and-dirty slow until your enchanter/shaman manages to get a more effective slow/mez on the mobs.<br><br>The slow on this song is the best we get prior to level 60 - the same as the slow on Chain (23) and Largo's (51), our single-target slows.  It is a better slow than our other two AE slows, Cessation (48) and Strane (54).  It's a fairly modest slow at around 20% when you first get the song, but somewhere in the late 30s it jumps up to about 30% (Chain does the same thing).<br><br>Be careful of stacking issues though.  I don't remember exactly which of these conflict, but I'm pretty sure 20 will block 51, which does not bode well if you're using 20 to slow and plan to switch to 51 to stop runners.  Test the combo you plan to use in a newbie zone before trying it for real.<br><br>Yes it's AE, but so many of our songs are AE that to become an exemplary bard, you really need to learn how to use AE in dungeons.  Avoid obvious mistakes (don't AE near walls, don't AE near pit traps or ledges, etc).  Test the safety of AE in low-risk situations to learn where it's safe (e.g. don't try out AE for the first time when you and 30 guildmembers are heading deep in a dungeon to attack a triggered mob for an epic quest).   The more you try AE in dungeons, the more you'll learn when and where it's safe to use.  You'll find that there are actually very few places where it's unsafe to use AE.</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>One of my favorites - </b>1/31/01 10:31:16 PM<br>~ <b>Faethore Ferenczy</b><blockquote>This is a great song out doors.  Do not play AE songs in dungeons.  It makes for bad JuJu hehe.  Try twisting DDD with binding for some serrious AC debuffing.  And watch your party really tear into the critters.<br><br>Faethore Ferenczy<br>Bard of the 41st Composition<br>Cosignee of the Honored<br>Reckoning of Honor (www.reckoningofhonor.com)<br>Tarrew Marr</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
